msgid "DNS and subdomains for the applications"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: docs/admin/45.tutorials/05.domains/dns_subdomains.mdx:5
#: docs/admin/45.tutorials/05.domains/dns_nohost_me.mdx:19
#, no-wrap
msgid "Subdomains"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/45.tutorials/05.domains/dns_subdomains.mdx:8
msgid ""
"YunoHost allows the use of subdomains. If one owns a domain name "
"`mydomain.com`, one first needs to create the subdomains in the DNS "
"configuration (with one's registrar like Gandi)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: docs/admin/45.tutorials/05.domains/dns_subdomains.mdx:9
#, no-wrap
msgid "Configuration example with Gandi"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/45.tutorials/05.domains/dns_subdomains.mdx:12
msgid ""
"The DNS configuration needs an A record with an IPv4 address, an AAAA record "
"with an IPv6 address, and various CNAME records, one for each desired "
"subdomain."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/45.tutorials/05.domains/dns_subdomains.mdx:14
msgid "If your DNS configuration looks like:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (text)
#: docs/admin/45.tutorials/05.domains/dns_subdomains.mdx:15
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"@         A            XYZ.XYZ.XYZ.XYZ\n"
"@         AAAA         1234:1234:1234:FFAA:FFAA:FFAA:FFAA:AAFF\n"
"*         CNAME        mydomain.com.\n"
"agenda    CNAME        mydomain.com.\n"
"blog      CNAME        mydomain.com.\n"
"rss       CNAME        mydomain.com.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/45.tutorials/05.domains/dns_subdomains.mdx:25
msgid ""
"then you can access `agenda.mydomain.com`, `blog.mydomain.com` and "
"`rss.mydomain.com` subdomains."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: docs/admin/45.tutorials/05.domains/dns_subdomains.mdx:26
#, no-wrap
msgid "Install an application on a subdomain"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/45.tutorials/05.domains/dns_subdomains.mdx:29
msgid ""
"To install an application on a subdomain in YunoHost, for example "
"`blog.mydomain.com`, the configuration is done in the administration panel. "
"One first add the subdomain to the available domains list. The creation of a "
"subdomain in YunoHost will create the corresponding configuration files for "
"NGINX (the web server used in YunoHost)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/45.tutorials/05.domains/dns_subdomains.mdx:31
#, no-wrap
msgid "Then, in the applications>install panel, one follows the classic installation process by choosing the desired subdomain as domain (for example `blog.mydomain.com`). One needs to choose the path `/` (in place of `/wordpress` for example). A warning message will appear telling that it won't be possible to install other application to this subdomain. After validation, the installation starts.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/45.tutorials/05.domains/dns_subdomains.mdx:33
msgid ""
"The application is then available at `blog.mydomain.com` (and not "
"`mydomain.com/wordpress`)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: docs/admin/45.tutorials/05.domains/dns_subdomains.mdx:34
#, no-wrap
msgid "Moving an application to a subdomain"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/45.tutorials/05.domains/dns_subdomains.mdx:40
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"What happens if the application is already installed? For example, one wants to move `mydomain.com/wordpress` to `blog.mydomain.com`.\n"
"It depends on the application.\n"
"Some applications allow the change of domain. In that case, one can proceed to the change through the administration panel: Applications > the_app_name > change URL.\n"
"If the application doesn't allow URL change, then there is no easy way to do it. The best solution is to reinstall the application.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: docs/admin/45.tutorials/05.domains/dns_subdomains.mdx:41
#, no-wrap
msgid "Reinstalling an application"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/45.tutorials/05.domains/dns_subdomains.mdx:43
msgid ""
"First, save the application data through the backup process. Then uninstall "
"the application with the administration panel. Then reinstall the "
"application to the desired domain. Finally, restore the backup."
msgstr ""
